te> Wow, it is a good article. Of all the thousands of column inches already written, and that will be written on this affair, this, I suspect, will be the one article worth reading. \n<p>Its main strength comes because it it is difficult for ordinary people to appreciate why what Snowden has done is important. </p> \n<p>Ellsberg lays out very clearly for us why : </p> \n<p>- the US constitution, meant to protect the people, has been virtually suspended<br />- secret courts<br />- oversight &quot;co-opted by the agencies they supposedly monitor&quot;<br /><b>[&quot;as with issues of torture, kidnapping, detention, assassination by drones and death squads&quot;]</b></p> \n<p>When these kind of things happen, government by tyranny has already begun its slow creep towards ordinary people who think it is all in their best interests. People get extraordinarily rendited on the slimmest of evidence, whole villages are bombed, &quot;in our best interests&quot;, and because they are far away and the individuals characterised as oddballs and dangerous (by the people making them disappear), all is all right. For now. Till it is you. Or your nearest and dearest.</p> \n<p>When William Hague says, &quot;law abiding citizens have nothing to fear&quot;, you know that they should be very afraid. Those words should send a chill down your spine. the law is quietly being changed and undermined, as Ellsberg makes clear here.</p> \n<p>We owe Ellsberg a big thank you for this article, just as the Vietnamese and the parents of those being sent to their deaths in Vietnam are in his debt for the exposing of the hollowness of the reasons for that war.</p> \n<p>Daniel Ellsberg, Bradly Manning, Edward Snowden. Extraordinary people.</p>\n                \n            </div>\n            \n                <div class=\"d-comment__actions\">\n                    <div class=\"d-comment__actions__main\">\n                        <a href=\"http://discussion.guardian.co.uk/components/report-abuse/24213