itical consensus - you have the political mainstream all representing slightly different shades of the same colour; then, by contrast, at the other end of the public sphere and discourse - there's a bunch of paranoid conspiracy theorists. Do you ever get the feeling the two polars might be somehow connected? The lack of representation, the shallow acceptance, and the paranoia? The point I'm attempting to make is that the moderates, and those wanting to live in a vaguely social democratic settlement - do not seem intent on excusing themselves from the table of radical neoliberalism - in order to settle around another table and begin a different political dialogue. </p> \n<p>As a result; the only public and passionate opposition to what's going on is from alternative comedians, conspiracy theorists, and columnists in The Guardian, or The Independent. This is not a heathy position for a supposed democracy to be, and surely you agree? </p> \n<p>If so, for individuals - such as yourself - to suggest that other people who happen stray from the radical orthodoxy of corporate neoliberalism, and towards criticism - somehow - turns them into &quot;neo-Marxist conspiracy theorists&quot; - does absolutely nothing for the cause of the centre-left, or left-liberals, of which you claim association. Rather, it serves the interests and agendas of those at the other end of the spectrum, who want things to continue as they are, and to further feed paranoia and crazed conspiracies. </p> \n<p>That way lies America - and I think we're already too far in that direction, don't you?</p>\n                \n            </div>\n            \n                <div class=\"d-comment__actions\">\n                    <div class=\"d-comment__actions__main\">\n                        <a href=\"http://discussion.guardian.co.uk/components/report-abuse/24218670\" class=\"d-comment__action d-comment__action--report\" target=\"_blank\">Report</a>\n                    </div>\n                </div>\n      