57000\">\n                        10 Jun 2013\n                    </time>\n                </div>\n            </div>\n        </div>\n        <div class=\"d-comment__main\">\n            <div class=\"d-comment__body\">\n                \n                    <p>@GM Potts - 10 June 2013 11:55am<br />While we are mentioning books I can highly recommend Daniel Ellsberg's Secrets: A Memoir of Vietnam and the Pentagon Papers.</p> \n<p>It is extremely relevant to the issues here and contains fascinating insights, such as the complete disdain of the administration for the public, the extent to which loyalty to your boss mattered far more than getting the issues right, the way groupthink slowly edges the system towards disaster and much, much more.</p> \n<p>Here he is on finding a way to suggest that the United States risked performing an act of outright aggression - that it would be in the wrong:<br /></p> \n<blockquote> \n <p>I took care to tender that word not as a compelling, objective judgement or as my own. It expressed how our bombing a country that had made no overt attack against us would possibly be &quot;seen&quot; or condemned by <i>others</i>. There was no other way to get such a thought into official discussion internally even once and remain employed. </p> \n <p>I'm sure that's still true.</p> \n <p>The same holds for the words &quot;criminal&quot; and &quot;immoral&quot; applied to a policy that one's agency or the president might favor or has adopted.</p> \n</blockquote> \n<p>If you work in a bureacracy, toe the line, even when things start to give off a high, fishy odour.</p>\n                \n            </div>\n            \n                <div class=\"d-comment__actions\">\n                    <div class=\"d-comment__actions__main\">\n                        <a href=\"http://discussion.guardian.co.uk/components/report-abuse/24218331\" class=\"d-comment__action d-comment__action--report\" target=\"_blank\">Report</a>\n                    </div>\n     